In this study, we simulated the Missing Completely At Random (MCAR) scenario for each dataset by introducing missing values at three levels: 2%, 5%, and 10%. As depicted in Figure 2, we randomly replaced original values in each column with NA based on the specified percentage of missingness. We employed a multiple imputation algorithm to fill in the missing values. Subsequently, we compared rows where imputation was performed to rows where no imputation was performed and calculated evaluation metrics. This process was iterated 30 times, and the mean of the evaluation metrics was taken across these iterations.
